00:00:21.660 --> 00:00:24.430
PROFESSOR: So we're through
with techniques of

00:00:24.430 --> 00:00:26.730
integration, which is really the
most technical thing that

00:00:26.730 --> 00:00:28.040
we're going to be doing.

00:00:28.040 --> 00:00:33.200
And now we're just
clearing up a few

00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:37.080
loose ends about calculus.

00:00:37.080 --> 00:00:40.810
And the one we're going to talk
about today will allow us

00:00:40.810 --> 00:00:45.530
to deal with infinity.

00:00:45.530 --> 00:00:50.940
And it's what's known
as L'Hopital's Rule.

00:00:50.940 --> 00:00:55.990
Here's L'Hopital's Rule.

00:00:55.990 --> 00:01:01.360
And that's what we're
going to do today.

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:14.990
L'Hopital's Rule it's also known
as L'Hospital's Rule.

00:01:14.990 --> 00:01:19.840
That's the same name, since the
circumflex is what you put

00:01:19.840 --> 00:01:25.610
in French to omit the s.

00:01:25.610 --> 00:01:27.290
So it's the same thing, and
it's still pronounced

00:01:27.290 --> 00:01:29.840
L'Hopital, even if it's
got an s in it.

00:01:29.840 --> 00:01:32.160
Alright, so that's the
first thing you need

00:01:32.160 --> 00:01:33.650
to know about it.

00:01:33.650 --> 00:01:42.040
And what this method does is,
it's a convenient way to

00:01:42.040 --> 00:01:55.410
calculate limits including
some new ones.

00:01:55.410 --> 00:02:02.670
So it'll be convenient
for the old ones.

00:02:02.670 --> 00:02:09.310
There are going to be some new
ones and, as an example, you

00:02:09.310 --> 00:02:14.910
can calculate x ln x as
x goes to infinity.

00:02:14.910 --> 00:02:17.100
You could, whoops, that's not a
very interesting one, let's

00:02:17.100 --> 00:02:20.470
try x goes to 0 from
the positive side.

00:02:20.470 --> 00:02:26.590
And you can calculate, for
example, x e^ - x, as x goes

00:02:26.590 --> 00:02:30.190
to infinity.

00:02:30.190 --> 00:02:37.340
And, well, maybe I should
include a few others.

00:02:37.340 --> 00:02:46.550
Maybe something like ln x /
x as x goes to infinity.

00:02:46.550 --> 00:02:50.580
So these are some examples of
things which, in fact, if you

00:02:50.580 --> 00:02:52.380
plug into your calculator,
you can see what's

00:02:52.380 --> 00:02:53.220
happening with these.

00:02:53.220 --> 00:02:56.430
But if you want to understand
them systematically, it's much

00:02:56.430 --> 00:03:00.140
better to have this tool
of L'Hopital's Rule.

00:03:00.140 --> 00:03:02.970
And certainly there isn't
a proof just based on a

00:03:02.970 --> 00:03:05.310
calculation in a calculator.

00:03:05.310 --> 00:03:07.760
So now here's the idea.

00:03:07.760 --> 00:03:11.750
I'll illustrate the idea
first with an example.

00:03:11.750 --> 00:03:13.380
And then we'll make
it systematic.

00:03:13.380 --> 00:03:15.020
And then we're going
to generalize it.

00:03:15.020 --> 00:03:18.840
We'll make it much more, so
when it includes these new

00:03:18.840 --> 00:03:21.330
limits, there are some little
pieces of trickiness that you

00:03:21.330 --> 00:03:23.050
have to understand.

00:03:23.050 --> 00:03:28.850
So, let's just take an example
that you could have done in

00:03:28.850 --> 00:03:31.070
the very first unit
of this class.

00:03:31.070 --> 00:03:41.230
The limit as x goes to 1 of
x ^ 10 - 1 / x ^2 - 1.

00:03:41.230 --> 00:03:45.370
So that's a limit that
we could've handled.

00:03:45.370 --> 00:03:48.110
And the thing that's
interesting, I mean, if you

00:03:48.110 --> 00:03:50.070
like this is in this category
that we mentioned at the

00:03:50.070 --> 00:03:52.480
beginning of the course
of interesting limits.

00:03:52.480 --> 00:03:55.750
What's interesting about it is
that if you do this silly

00:03:55.750 --> 00:04:00.700
thing, which is just plug in
x = 1, at x = 1 you're

00:04:00.700 --> 00:04:02.480
going to get 0 / 0.

00:04:02.480 --> 00:04:12.720
And that's what we call
an indeterminate form.

00:04:12.720 --> 00:04:15.340
It's just unclear what it is.

00:04:15.340 --> 00:04:18.150
From that plugging, in you
just can't get it.

00:04:18.150 --> 00:04:19.490
Now, on the other
hand, there's a

00:04:19.490 --> 00:04:21.360
trick for doing this.

00:04:21.360 --> 00:04:23.960
And this is the trick
that we did at the

00:04:23.960 --> 00:04:25.350
beginning of the class.

00:04:25.350 --> 00:04:32.040
And the idea is I can divide
in the numerator and

00:04:32.040 --> 00:04:36.230
denominator by x - 1.

00:04:36.230 --> 00:04:43.060
So this limit is unchanged, if
I try to cancel the hidden

00:04:43.060 --> 00:04:46.400
factor x - 1 in the numerator
and denominator.

00:04:46.400 --> 00:04:51.630
Now, we can actually carry out
these ratios of polynomials

00:04:51.630 --> 00:04:54.580
and calculate them by long
division in algebra.

00:04:54.580 --> 00:04:55.660
That's very, very long.

00:04:55.660 --> 00:04:57.110
We want to do this
with calculus.

00:04:57.110 --> 00:05:01.170
And we already have. We already
know that this ratio

00:05:01.170 --> 00:05:03.420
is what's called a difference
quotient.

00:05:03.420 --> 00:05:06.380
And then in the limit, it tends
to the derivative of

00:05:06.380 --> 00:05:08.340
this function.

00:05:08.340 --> 00:05:12.390
So the idea is that this is
actually equal to, in the

00:05:12.390 --> 00:05:15.400
limit, now let's just study
one piece of it.

00:05:15.400 --> 00:05:21.150
So if I have a function f ( x),
which is x ^ 10 - 1, and

00:05:21.150 --> 00:05:26.710
the value at 1 happens to
be equal to 0, then this

00:05:26.710 --> 00:05:32.350
expression that we have, which
is in disguise, this is in

00:05:32.350 --> 00:05:38.300
disguise the difference
quotient, tends to, as x goes

00:05:38.300 --> 00:05:43.030
to 1, the derivative,
which is f' ( 1).

00:05:43.030 --> 00:05:43.620
That's what it is.

00:05:43.620 --> 00:05:46.090
So we know what the numerator
goes to, and similarly we'll

00:05:46.090 --> 00:05:47.650
know what the denominator
goes to.

00:05:47.650 --> 00:05:51.580
But what is that?

00:05:51.580 --> 00:05:58.460
Well, f ' (x) = 10x ^ 9.

00:05:58.460 --> 00:06:00.610
So we know what the answer is.

00:06:00.610 --> 00:06:03.550
In the numerator it's 10x ^ 9.

00:06:03.550 --> 00:06:06.470
In the denominator, it's going
to be 2x, that's the

00:06:06.470 --> 00:06:08.340
derivative of x ^2 - 1.

00:06:08.340 --> 00:06:13.930
And then were going to have
to evaluate that at x = 1.

00:06:13.930 --> 00:06:18.160
And so it's going to be
10/2, which is 5.

00:06:18.160 --> 00:06:19.350
So the answer is 5.

00:06:19.350 --> 00:06:23.050
And it's pretty easy to get
from our techniques and

00:06:23.050 --> 00:06:26.580
knowledge of derivatives,
using this rather clever

00:06:26.580 --> 00:06:27.510
algebraic trick.

00:06:27.510 --> 00:06:33.540
This business of dividing
by x - 1.

00:06:33.540 --> 00:06:38.030
What I want to do now is just
carry this method out

00:06:38.030 --> 00:06:39.420
systematically.

00:06:39.420 --> 00:06:44.290
And that's going to give us the
approach to what's known

00:06:44.290 --> 00:06:45.260
as L'Hopital's Rule.

00:06:45.260 --> 00:06:48.860
What my main subject
for today.

00:06:48.860 --> 00:06:50.040
So here's the idea.

00:06:50.040 --> 00:06:53.530
Suppose we're considering, in
general, a limit as x goes to

00:06:53.530 --> 00:06:58.860
some number a of f
( x) / g ( x).

00:06:58.860 --> 00:07:02.330
And suppose it's the bad case
where we can't decide.

00:07:02.330 --> 00:07:09.200
So it's in determinate.
f ( a) = g ( a) = 0.

00:07:09.200 --> 00:07:11.730
So it would be 0 / 0.

00:07:11.730 --> 00:07:13.580
Now we're just going to
do exactly the same

00:07:13.580 --> 00:07:15.520
thing we did over here.

00:07:15.520 --> 00:07:19.170
Namely, we're going to divide
a numerator and denominator,

00:07:19.170 --> 00:07:21.010
and we're going to repeat
that argument.

00:07:21.010 --> 00:07:25.390
So we have here f
( x) / x - a.

00:07:25.390 --> 00:07:30.240
And g (x) / x - a also.

00:07:30.240 --> 00:07:33.200
I haven't changed
anything yet.

00:07:33.200 --> 00:07:38.120
And now I'm going to write it
in this suggestive form.

00:07:38.120 --> 00:07:41.050
Namely, I'm going to take
separately the limit in the

00:07:41.050 --> 00:07:42.330
numerator and the denominator.

00:07:42.330 --> 00:07:44.460
And I'm going to make
one more shift.

00:07:44.460 --> 00:07:47.250
So I'm going to take the limit,
as x goes to a in the

00:07:47.250 --> 00:07:49.960
numerator, but I'm going
to write it as f ( x) -

00:07:49.960 --> 00:07:53.270
f ( a) / x - a.

00:07:53.270 --> 00:07:54.870
So that's the way I'm going to
write the numerator, and I've

00:07:54.870 --> 00:07:57.580
got to draw a much
longer line here.

00:07:57.580 --> 00:07:59.720
So why am I allowed
to do that?

00:07:59.720 --> 00:08:02.690
That's because f (a) = 0.

00:08:02.690 --> 00:08:07.000
So I didn't change this
numerator of the numerator any

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:12.210
by subtracting. f ( a) = 0.

00:08:12.210 --> 00:08:19.260
And I'll do the same thing
to the denominator.

00:08:19.260 --> 00:08:22.650
Again, g ( a) = 0,
so this is OK.

00:08:22.650 --> 00:08:25.760
And lo and behold, I know
what these limits are.

00:08:25.760 --> 00:08:34.110
This is f ' (a) / g '(a).

00:08:34.110 --> 00:08:34.660
So that's it.

00:08:34.660 --> 00:08:36.880
That's the technique and this
evaluates the limit.

00:08:36.880 --> 00:08:38.070
And it's not so difficult.

00:08:38.070 --> 00:08:40.310
The formula's pretty
straightforward here.

00:08:40.310 --> 00:08:51.410
And it works, provided that
g ' (a) is not 0.

00:08:51.410 --> 00:08:52.590
Yeah, question.

00:08:52.590 --> 00:09:05.040
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:09:05.040 --> 00:09:10.900
PROFESSOR: The question is, is
there a more intuitive way of

00:09:10.900 --> 00:09:14.210
understanding this procedure.

00:09:14.210 --> 00:09:21.650
And I think the short answer
is that there are other,

00:09:21.650 --> 00:09:22.600
similar, ways.

00:09:22.600 --> 00:09:25.520
I don't consider them to
be more intuitive.

00:09:25.520 --> 00:09:28.180
I will be mentioning one of
them, which is the idea of

00:09:28.180 --> 00:09:33.280
linearization, which goes back
to what we did in Unit 2.

00:09:33.280 --> 00:09:35.480
I think it's very important to
understand all of these, more

00:09:35.480 --> 00:09:36.810
or less, at once.

00:09:36.810 --> 00:09:39.530
But I wouldn't claim that any
of these methods is a more

00:09:39.530 --> 00:09:41.890
intuitive one than the other.

00:09:41.890 --> 00:09:43.830
But basically what's happening
is, we're looking at the

00:09:43.830 --> 00:09:46.340
linear approximation
to f, at a.

00:09:46.340 --> 00:09:48.980
And the linear approximation
to g at a.

00:09:48.980 --> 00:09:52.880
That's what underlies this.

00:09:52.880 --> 00:09:56.630
So now I get to formulate for
you L'Hopital's Rule at least

00:09:56.630 --> 00:09:59.430
in what I would call the
easy version or, if you

00:09:59.430 --> 00:10:00.520
like, Version 1.

00:10:00.520 --> 00:10:10.290
So here's L'Hopital's Rule.

00:10:10.290 --> 00:10:15.290
Version 1.

00:10:15.290 --> 00:10:18.480
It's not going to be quite the
same as what we just did.

00:10:18.480 --> 00:10:20.670
It's going to be much,
much better.

00:10:20.670 --> 00:10:22.860
And more useful.

00:10:22.860 --> 00:10:25.840
And what is going to take care
of is this problem that the

00:10:25.840 --> 00:10:29.730
denominator is not 0.

00:10:29.730 --> 00:10:31.420
So now here's what we're
going to do.

00:10:31.420 --> 00:10:35.000
We're going to say that it turns
out that the limit a x

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:44.480
goes to a of f(x) / g ( x) = the
limit as x goes to a to a

00:10:44.480 --> 00:10:48.210
f '(x) / g' (x).

00:10:48.210 --> 00:10:50.160
Now, that looks practically
the same as

00:10:50.160 --> 00:10:51.380
what we said before.

00:10:51.380 --> 00:10:55.310
And I have to make sure that you
understand when it works.

00:10:55.310 --> 00:11:02.820
So it works provided this is
one of these undefined

00:11:02.820 --> 00:11:03.430
expressions.

00:11:03.430 --> 00:11:06.700
In other words, f (
a) = g ( a) = 0.

00:11:06.700 --> 00:11:11.320
So we have a 0 / 0 expression,
indeterminant.

00:11:11.320 --> 00:11:15.280
And, also, we need one
more assumption.

00:11:15.280 --> 00:11:30.360
And the right-hand side, the
right-hand limit exists.

00:11:30.360 --> 00:11:33.510
Now, this is practically
the same thing as

00:11:33.510 --> 00:11:35.310
what I said over here.

00:11:35.310 --> 00:11:41.050
Namely, I took the ratio of
these functions, x ^ 10 - 1

00:11:41.050 --> 00:11:42.540
and x ^2 - 1.

00:11:42.540 --> 00:11:45.460
I took their derivatives, which
is what I did right

00:11:45.460 --> 00:11:46.180
here, right.

00:11:46.180 --> 00:11:48.480
I just differentiated them
and I took the ratio.

00:11:48.480 --> 00:11:51.680
This is way easier than the
quotient rule, and is nothing

00:11:51.680 --> 00:11:53.780
like the quotient rule.

00:11:53.780 --> 00:11:56.900
Don't think quotient rule.

00:11:56.900 --> 00:11:58.070
Don't think quotient rule.

00:11:58.070 --> 00:12:00.360
So we differentiate the
numerator and denominator

00:12:00.360 --> 00:12:02.400
separately.

00:12:02.400 --> 00:12:08.030
And then I take the limit as
x goes to 1 and I get 5.

00:12:08.030 --> 00:12:09.940
So that's what I'm claiming
over here.

00:12:09.940 --> 00:12:12.275
I take these functions, I
replace them with this ratio

00:12:12.275 --> 00:12:14.000
of derivatives, and then
I take the limit

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:15.650
instead, over here.

00:12:15.650 --> 00:12:18.020
And it turned out that the
functions got much simpler

00:12:18.020 --> 00:12:19.120
when I differentiated them.

00:12:19.120 --> 00:12:21.790
I started with this messy object
and I got this much

00:12:21.790 --> 00:12:25.520
easier object that I could
easily evaluate.

00:12:25.520 --> 00:12:29.830
So that's the big game that's
happening here.

00:12:29.830 --> 00:12:33.495
It works, if this limit makes
sense and this limit exists.

00:12:33.495 --> 00:12:38.130
Now, notice I didn't claim that
g, that the denominator,

00:12:38.130 --> 00:12:40.260
had to be non-0.

00:12:40.260 --> 00:12:42.070
So that's what's going
to help us a little

00:12:42.070 --> 00:12:43.430
bit in a few examples.

00:12:43.430 --> 00:12:45.650
So let me give you a couple
of examples and

00:12:45.650 --> 00:12:46.570
then we'll go further.

00:12:46.570 --> 00:12:48.470
Now, this is only Version 1.

00:12:48.470 --> 00:12:51.340
But first we have to understand
how this one works.

00:12:51.340 --> 00:12:56.300
So here's another example.

00:12:56.300 --> 00:13:06.400
Take the limit as x goes to
0, of sin 5x / sin 2x.

00:13:06.400 --> 00:13:10.060
This is another kind of example
of a limit that we

00:13:10.060 --> 00:13:12.350
discussed in the first
part of the course.

00:13:12.350 --> 00:13:13.930
Unfortunately, now we're
reviewing stuff.

00:13:13.930 --> 00:13:15.980
So this should reinforce
what you did there.

00:13:15.980 --> 00:13:20.330
This will be an easier way
of thinking about it.

00:13:20.330 --> 00:13:25.050
So by L'Hopital's Rule,
so here's the step.

00:13:25.050 --> 00:13:27.870
We're going to take one
of these steps.

00:13:27.870 --> 00:13:31.560
This is the limit, as x goes to
1, of the derivatives here.

00:13:31.560 --> 00:13:43.220
So that's 5 cos 5x / 2 cos 2x.

00:13:43.220 --> 00:13:46.735
The limit was 1 over there,
but now it's 0. a

00:13:46.735 --> 00:13:48.530
is 0 in this case.

00:13:48.530 --> 00:13:51.500
This is the number a.

00:13:51.500 --> 00:13:54.930
Thank you.

00:13:54.930 --> 00:13:58.760
So the limit as x goes to 0 is
the same as the limit of the

00:13:58.760 --> 00:14:01.400
derivatives.

00:14:01.400 --> 00:14:02.620
And that's easy to evaluate.

00:14:02.620 --> 00:14:04.910
Cosine of 0 = 1, right.

00:14:04.910 --> 00:14:10.550
This is equal to
5 (cos (5* 0).

00:14:10.550 --> 00:14:12.840
And that's a multiplication
sign.

00:14:12.840 --> 00:14:14.660
Maybe I should just
write this as 0.

00:14:14.660 --> 00:14:17.240
Divided by 2 cos 0.

00:14:17.240 --> 00:14:24.440
But you know that that's 5/2.

00:14:24.440 --> 00:14:27.340
So this is how L'Hopital's
method works.

00:14:27.340 --> 00:14:33.660
It's pretty painless.

00:14:33.660 --> 00:14:36.540
I'm going to give you another
example, which shows that it

00:14:36.540 --> 00:14:39.010
works a little better
than the method that

00:14:39.010 --> 00:14:45.550
I started out with.

00:14:45.550 --> 00:14:48.380
Here's what happens if we
consider the function

00:14:48.380 --> 00:14:55.470
cos x - 1 / x ^2.

00:14:55.470 --> 00:14:57.940
That was a little harder
to deal with.

00:14:57.940 --> 00:15:03.060
And again, this is one of these
0 / 0 things near x = 0.

00:15:03.060 --> 00:15:11.200
As x tends to 0, this goes to
an indeterminate form here.

00:15:11.200 --> 00:15:14.370
Now, according to our method,
this is equivalent to, now I'm

00:15:14.370 --> 00:15:16.630
going to use this little wiggle
because I don't want to

00:15:16.630 --> 00:15:20.030
write limit, limit, limit,
limit a million times.

00:15:20.030 --> 00:15:22.330
So I'm going to use a
little wiggle here.

00:15:22.330 --> 00:15:26.840
So as x goes to 0, this is going
to behave the same way

00:15:26.840 --> 00:15:30.390
as differentiating numerator
and denominator.

00:15:30.390 --> 00:15:33.640
So again this is going to be
- sin x in the numerator.

00:15:33.640 --> 00:15:42.110
In the denominator, it's
going to be 2x.

00:15:42.110 --> 00:15:47.140
Now, notice that we still
haven't won yet.

00:15:47.140 --> 00:15:51.060
Because this is still
of 0 / 0 type.

00:15:51.060 --> 00:15:54.000
When you plug in x =
0 you still get 0.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:57.270
But that doesn't damage
the method.

00:15:57.270 --> 00:16:00.630
That doesn't make
the method fail.

00:16:00.630 --> 00:16:03.270
This 0 / 0, we can
apply L'Hopital's

00:16:03.270 --> 00:16:10.410
Rule a second time.

00:16:10.410 --> 00:16:13.120
And as x goes to 0 this is
the same thing as, again,

00:16:13.120 --> 00:16:14.860
differentiating the numerator
and denominator.

00:16:14.860 --> 00:16:19.900
So here I get - cos x in the
numerator, and I get 2 in the

00:16:19.900 --> 00:16:22.480
denominator.

