e^ p x / 100 / 1) ^ 100.

00:33:55.830 --> 00:34:02.480
That's our L'Hopital's step.

00:34:02.480 --> 00:34:09.310
And of course, that's (infinity
/ 1 ) ^ 100.

00:34:09.310 --> 00:34:10.410
Which is infinity.

00:34:10.410 --> 00:34:14.360
Now, again I did this in a
slightly different way to show

00:34:14.360 --> 00:34:16.800
you that it works with
infinity as well.

00:34:16.800 --> 00:34:18.400
So that was this other case.

00:34:18.400 --> 00:34:21.010
The right-hand side can
exist, or it can be

00:34:21.010 --> 00:34:22.460
plus or minus infinity.

00:34:22.460 --> 00:34:25.240
And that applies
to this limit.

00:34:25.240 --> 00:34:27.990
And therefore, to the
original limit.

00:34:27.990 --> 00:34:35.550
And the conclusion here is
that e ^ px, p &gt; 0, grows

00:34:35.550 --> 00:34:46.340
faster than any power of x.

00:34:46.340 --> 00:34:49.600
I picked x ^ 100, but obviously
it didn't matter

00:34:49.600 --> 00:34:52.670
what power I picked.

00:34:52.670 --> 00:35:02.050
The exponents beat
all the powers.

00:35:02.050 --> 00:35:04.340
So we have one more of the
ones that I gave at the

00:35:04.340 --> 00:35:07.780
beginning to take care of.

00:35:07.780 --> 00:35:11.330
And that one is the logarithm.

00:35:11.330 --> 00:35:15.720
And its behavior at infinity.

00:35:15.720 --> 00:35:18.700
So I'll do a slightly variant
on that one, too.

00:35:18.700 --> 00:35:25.080
So we have Example 6, which is
ln x, and instead of dividing

00:35:25.080 --> 00:35:27.780
by x, I'm going to
divide by x^ 1/3.

00:35:27.780 --> 00:35:30.650
I could divide by any positive
power of x, we'll just do this

00:35:30.650 --> 00:35:32.170
example here.

00:35:32.170 --> 00:35:38.340
So now this, as x goes to
infinity, is of the form

00:35:38.340 --> 00:35:43.230
infinity / infinity.

00:35:43.230 --> 00:35:47.530
And so it's equivalent to what
happens when I differentiate

00:35:47.530 --> 00:35:49.250
numerator and denominator
separately.

00:35:49.250 --> 00:36:00.320
And that's 1 / x, and here
I have 1/3 x ^ - 2/3.

00:36:00.320 --> 00:36:03.470
1 / x, and then 1/3 x^ - 2/3.

00:36:03.470 --> 00:36:05.920
Now, when the dust settles
here and you get your

00:36:05.920 --> 00:36:10.560
exponents right, we have an x^ -
1, and this is an x ^ + 2/3,

00:36:10.560 --> 00:36:12.500
and that's a 1/3 becomes a 3.

00:36:12.500 --> 00:36:19.260
So this is what it is.

00:36:19.260 --> 00:36:26.480
And that's equal
to 3x ^ - 1/3.

00:36:26.480 --> 00:36:27.830
Which we can decide.

00:36:27.830 --> 00:36:30.150
It goes to 0.

00:36:30.150 --> 00:36:37.240
As x goes to infinity.

00:36:37.240 --> 00:36:49.910
And so the conclusion is that
ln x grows more slowly as x

00:36:49.910 --> 00:37:08.690
goes to infinity, than x ^ 1/3
or any positive power of x.

00:37:08.690 --> 00:37:15.500
So any x ^ p, p positive,
will work.

00:37:15.500 --> 00:37:17.670
So ln is really slow,
going to infinity.

00:37:17.670 --> 00:37:20.550
It's very, very gradual.

00:37:20.550 --> 00:37:21.420
Yeah, question.

00:37:21.420 --> 00:37:45.970
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:37:45.970 --> 00:37:48.230
PROFESSOR: The question
is, how many

00:37:48.230 --> 00:37:50.630
hypotheses do you need here?

00:37:50.630 --> 00:37:57.760
So I said that, and I think what
you were asking is, if I

00:37:57.760 --> 00:38:02.940
have this hypothesis, can I
also have this hypothesis.

00:38:02.940 --> 00:38:04.870
That's OK.

00:38:04.870 --> 00:38:08.840
I can have this hypothesis
combined with this one.

00:38:08.840 --> 00:38:11.280
I need something about
f (a) and g ( a).

00:38:11.280 --> 00:38:14.910
I can't assume nothing
about f(a) and g(a).

00:38:14.910 --> 00:38:17.370
So in other words, I have to
be faced with either an

00:38:17.370 --> 00:38:24.180
infinity / infinity, or
a 0 / 0 situation.

00:38:24.180 --> 00:38:26.650
So let's see.

00:38:26.650 --> 00:38:35.160
A rule applies in the 0 / 0, or
infinity / infinity case.

00:38:35.160 --> 00:38:40.910
These are the only two cases
that it applies in.

00:38:40.910 --> 00:38:45.370
And a can be anything.

00:38:45.370 --> 00:38:48.880
Including infinity.

00:38:48.880 --> 00:38:51.230
Plus or minus infinity.

00:38:51.230 --> 00:38:53.390
The rule applies in
these two cases.

00:38:53.390 --> 00:38:58.310
So in other words, this is
what f ( a) / g ( a) is.

00:38:58.310 --> 00:39:00.750
Either one of these.

00:39:00.750 --> 00:39:02.540
And in fact, it can
be plus or minus.

00:39:02.540 --> 00:39:06.460
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:39:06.460 --> 00:39:10.290
PROFESSOR: And the right-hand
side has to be something.

00:39:10.290 --> 00:39:21.250
It has to be either finite or
plus or minus infinity.

00:39:21.250 --> 00:39:23.690
So you need something.

00:39:23.690 --> 00:39:26.740
You need a specific value of a,
you need to decide whether

00:39:26.740 --> 00:39:28.070
it's an indeterminate form.

00:39:28.070 --> 00:39:31.390
And you need the right-hand
limit to exist. It's not hard

00:39:31.390 --> 00:39:33.530
to impose this.

00:39:33.530 --> 00:39:36.423
Because when you look at the
right-hand side, you'll want

00:39:36.423 --> 00:39:37.350
to be calculating it.

00:39:37.350 --> 00:39:38.600
So you want to know
what it is.

00:39:38.600 --> 00:39:47.640
So you'll never have problems
confirming this hypothesis.

00:39:47.640 --> 00:39:51.280
Alright.

00:39:51.280 --> 00:39:54.480
Let me give you one
more example here.

00:39:54.480 --> 00:39:56.600
Which is just slightly
trickier.

00:39:56.600 --> 00:40:15.130
Which involves, so here's
another indeterminate form.

00:40:15.130 --> 00:40:16.780
That's going to be 0 ^ 0.

00:40:20.530 --> 00:40:22.580
So there are lots of these
things where you just don't

00:40:22.580 --> 00:40:23.690
know what to do.

00:40:23.690 --> 00:40:27.730
And they come out in various
different ways.

00:40:27.730 --> 00:40:32.390
The simplest example of this
is the limit as x goes to 0

00:40:32.390 --> 00:40:41.430
from above of x ^ x.

00:40:41.430 --> 00:40:45.360
In order to work out what's
happening with this one, we

00:40:45.360 --> 00:40:47.610
have to use a trick.

00:40:47.610 --> 00:40:52.650
And the trick is this is
a moving exponent.

00:40:52.650 --> 00:40:56.220
And so it's appropriate
to use base e.

00:40:56.220 --> 00:40:59.010
This is something that we did
way back in the first unit.

00:40:59.010 --> 00:41:06.900
So, since we have a moving
exponent, we're

00:41:06.900 --> 00:41:11.830
going to use base e.

00:41:11.830 --> 00:41:13.690
That's the good base
to use whenever you

00:41:13.690 --> 00:41:15.600
have a moving exponent.

00:41:15.600 --> 00:41:21.530
And so rewrite this as
x^ x = e ^ x ln x.

00:41:21.530 --> 00:41:23.960
And now, in order to figure
out what's happening, we

00:41:23.960 --> 00:41:25.250
really only have to know what's

00:41:25.250 --> 00:41:32.140
going on with the exponent.

00:41:32.140 --> 00:41:34.100
So remember, actually
we already did this.

00:41:34.100 --> 00:41:36.100
But I'm going to do it
once more for you.

00:41:36.100 --> 00:41:39.340
This is ln x / (1 / x).

00:41:39.340 --> 00:41:43.360
And that's equivalent, as
x goes to 0, to using

00:41:43.360 --> 00:41:51.450
L'Hopital's Rule to 1 / x, and
this is - 1 / x ^2, which is -

00:41:51.450 --> 00:41:54.350
x, which goes to 0.

00:41:54.350 --> 00:41:58.030
As x goes to 0.

00:41:58.030 --> 00:42:01.670
And so what we have here is that
this one is going to be

00:42:01.670 --> 00:42:06.200
equivalent to, well, it's
going to tend to

00:42:06.200 --> 00:42:07.520
what we got over here.

00:42:07.520 --> 00:42:10.170
It's e ^ 0.

00:42:10.170 --> 00:42:13.980
That exponent is what we want.

00:42:13.980 --> 00:42:18.250
As x goes to 0.

00:42:18.250 --> 00:42:27.190
So that's the answer This
limit happens to be 1.

00:42:27.190 --> 00:42:30.050
That's actually relatively easy
to do, given all of the

00:42:30.050 --> 00:42:42.700
power that we have
at our hands.

00:42:42.700 --> 00:42:49.310
Now, let me give you
one more example.

00:42:49.310 --> 00:42:52.360
Suppose you're trying to
understand the limit

00:42:52.360 --> 00:42:59.060
of sin x / x ^2.

00:42:59.060 --> 00:43:06.320
If you apply L'Hopital's Rule,
as x goes to 0, you're going

00:43:06.320 --> 00:43:11.660
to get cos x / 2x.

00:43:11.660 --> 00:43:19.270
And if you apply L'Hopital's
Rule again, as x goes to 0,

00:43:19.270 --> 00:43:24.920
you're going to get
the - sin x / 2.

00:43:24.920 --> 00:43:35.840
And this, as x goes
to 0, goes to 0.

00:43:35.840 --> 00:43:39.820
On the other hand, if you look
at the linear approximation

00:43:39.820 --> 00:43:49.620
method, linear approximation
says that sin x is

00:43:49.620 --> 00:43:55.090
approximately x near 0.

00:43:55.090 --> 00:43:59.560
So that should be x / x ^2.

00:43:59.560 --> 00:44:04.900
Which is 1 / x, which
goes to infinity.

00:44:04.900 --> 00:44:08.980
As x goes to 0, at least from
one side, minus infinity to

00:44:08.980 --> 00:44:13.100
the other side.

00:44:13.100 --> 00:44:17.320
So there's something fishy
going on here, right?

00:44:17.320 --> 00:44:19.330
So this is fishy.

00:44:19.330 --> 00:44:21.520
Or maybe this is fishy,
I don't know.

00:44:21.520 --> 00:44:26.420
So, tell me what's wrong here.

00:44:26.420 --> 00:44:26.750
Yeah.

00:44:26.750 --> 00:44:37.120
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:44:37.120 --> 00:44:38.230
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:44:38.230 --> 00:44:43.070
So the claim is that the
second application of

00:44:43.070 --> 00:44:51.950
L'Hopital's Rule, this
one, is wrong.

00:44:51.950 --> 00:44:54.620
And that's correct.

00:44:54.620 --> 00:44:56.700
And this is where you
have to watch out,

00:44:56.700 --> 00:44:58.500
with L'Hopital's Rule.

00:44:58.500 --> 00:44:59.920
This is exactly where you
have to watch out.

00:44:59.920 --> 00:45:03.580
You have to apply the
test. Here it's an

00:45:03.580 --> 00:45:03.820
indeterminate form.

00:45:03.820 --> 00:45:08.260
It's 0 / 0 before I
applied the rule.

00:45:08.260 --> 00:45:11.290
But in order to apply the rule
the second time, it still has

00:45:11.290 --> 00:45:12.410
to be 0 / 0.

00:45:12.410 --> 00:45:14.170
But this one isn't.

00:45:14.170 --> 00:45:19.290
This one is 1 / 0.

00:45:19.290 --> 00:45:20.650
It's no longer an indeterminate
form.

00:45:20.650 --> 00:45:22.910
It's actually infinite.

00:45:22.910 --> 00:45:24.970
Either plus or minus, depending
on the sign of the

00:45:24.970 --> 00:45:25.520
denominator.

00:45:25.520 --> 00:45:27.970
Which is just what
this answer is.

00:45:27.970 --> 00:45:30.550
So the linear approximation
is safe.

00:45:30.550 --> 00:45:35.160
And we just applied L'Hopital's
Rule wrong.

00:45:35.160 --> 00:45:55.760
So the moral of the story here
is look before you L'Hop.

00:45:55.760 --> 00:45:58.260
Alright.

